{
  "texts": [
    "Weaker performance for antonyms has been observed for other work on estimating similarity using distributional information (Dou et al., 2018).",
    "Specifically, GPT-4 tended to rate antonym pairs as more similar on average than humans did (mean difference = 2.53, SD = 1.64).",
    "As with SimLex999, qualitative inspection revealed that a number of GPT-4's ratings diverge not only for antonyms, but for other verb pairs that form semantic \"complements\" (e.g., \"incline/decline\", \"win/defeat\", \"reap/sow\", \"push/ tug\", \"die/kill\", \"multiply/divide\", and \"spring/fall\").",
    "In each of these cases, GPT-4 rated the pair as more similar than humans did.",
    "RAW-C. GPT-4's performance on the RAW-C dataset was higher (rho = 0.82) than both human inter-annotator agreement (rho = 0.79) and past language models tested (rho = 0.58)."
  ]
}